<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,152,663]" pageId="7" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis box="[197,374,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="60">Male genitalia</emphasis>
. Pygophore(
<figureCitation box="[533,600,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[151,255,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[260,1323,1027,1883]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[252,1334,1018,1900]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Pedionis (Pedionis) yunnana sp. nov. A, pygophore, subgenital plates, lateral view; B, style, lateral view; C, aedeagus, dorsal connective, lateral view; D, aedeagus and dorsal connectives, caudal view; E, connective, lateral view; F, connective, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195501/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="60">
Fig. 
<number box="[585,600,152,178]" pageId="7" pageNumber="60" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
A) elongate, caudal margin produced into acutely angled process and one row of fine setae along ventral margin. Subgenital plate narrow and long, with marginal setae. Style and connective similar to those in 
<taxonomicName box="[516,715,226,251]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pedionis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="garuda">
<emphasis box="[516,715,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="60">Pedionis garuda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[867,951,226,252]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[151,255,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[260,1323,1027,1883]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[252,1334,1018,1900]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Pedionis (Pedionis) yunnana sp. nov. A, pygophore, subgenital plates, lateral view; B, style, lateral view; C, aedeagus, dorsal connective, lateral view; D, aedeagus and dorsal connectives, caudal view; E, connective, lateral view; F, connective, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/195501/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="60">
Figs. 
<number box="[936,951,226,252]" pageId="7" pageNumber="60" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
C, D) similar to that in 
<taxonomicName box="[1243,1381,226,251]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pedionis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lii">
<emphasis box="[1243,1381,226,251]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="60">Pedionis lii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but with one pair of slender spine-like processes apically; dorsal connective as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Huang and Viraktamath." authorityName="Huang and Viraktamath." class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pedionis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufoscutellata">
<emphasis box="[1075,1350,264,289]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="60">Pedionis rufoscutellata</emphasis>
Huang and Viraktamath.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,152,663]" pageId="7" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis box="[197,293,338,363]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="60">Female.</emphasis>
Similar in overall coloration to male. Ovipositor slightly projecting beyond pygophore. Seventh sternite convexly produced, median projection strongly concave apically.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
